                <h2>When to Use This SOP</h2>
<p>This guide applies to Meta ad campaigns that have run for at least 7 days with at least 20 conversions accumulated. Small sample sizes lead to misleading conclusions.  </p>
<hr />
<h2>Step 1: Export Data and Identify "Impression Drivers"</h2>
<h3>1.1 Data Export</h3>
<p>In Meta Ads Manager, export ad set-level data with these metrics:</p>
<ul>
<li>Amount spent</li>
<li>Impressions</li>
<li>Link clicks</li>
<li>Conversion events (your optimized event)</li>
<li>Cost per result (CPA)</li>
<li>Video watch time (for video creatives)</li>
</ul>
<h3>1.2 Setting "Impression Driver" Thresholds</h3>
<p>Sort creatives by spend descending and calculate averages for Top 10:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Metric</th>
<th>"Impression Driver" Benchmark</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>CTR</td>
<td>≥1.5% (Feed placement)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Video completion rate</td>
<td>≥25% (15-sec video)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>CPM</td>
<td>≤$15 (Mature markets)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Tip</strong>: If a creative has high CTR but also high CPM, it's competing aggressively for inventory—not necessarily a quality impression driver.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>1.3 Flag "Impression Driver" Candidates</h3>
<p>Creatives meeting any two thresholds enter the next validation step.  </p>
<hr />
<h2>Step 2: Cross-Validate Against "Revenue Generators"</h2>
<h3>2.1 Core "Revenue Generator" Metrics</h3>
<p>"Impression drivers" ≠ "Revenue generators." True revenue-generating creatives must meet:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>ROAS ≥ Target</strong>: Industry benchmarks vary—gaming typically requires ROAS ≥1.5, e-commerce demands higher returns</li>
<li><strong>CPA in Profitable Range</strong>: Cost per acquisition &lt; Average order value × Gross margin</li>
<li><strong>Conversion Volume ≥ Threshold</strong>: Minimum 10 conversions for statistical significance</li>
</ul>
<h3>2.2 Cross-Analysis Method</h3>
<p>Build a four-quadrant matrix:</p>
<pre><code>         High Conversions
              ↑
   Quadrant │ Quadrant
  A (Sell)  │ B (Star Creatives)
────────────┼────────────
   Quadrant │ Quadrant
  C (Test)  │ D (Optimize)
────────────┼────────────→ High CTR
 (Don't Run)│ (Impression Driver)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Quadrant A (Revenue + Low CTR)</strong>: Often overlooked but actually ROI-positive. Analyze landing page alignment and audience fit.</p>
<p><strong>Quadrant B (High CTR + Conversions)</strong>: Best performers. Extract creative elements for replication.</p>
<p><strong>Quadrant C (Low CTR + Low Conversions)</strong>: Immediately pause—don't waste budget optimizing.</p>
<p><strong>Quadrant D (High CTR + Low Conversions)</strong>: This is the problem we're solving—"impression drivers with no revenue."</p>
<h3>2.3 Root Causes of Quadrant D Creatives</h3>
<p>Isolate Quadrant D creatives and investigate:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Landing Page Alignment</strong>: Does the ad promise match the landing page content?</li>
<li><strong>CTA Visibility</strong>: Is the call-to-action above the fold on mobile?</li>
<li><strong>User Intent Mismatch</strong>: Are you attracting impulse-clickers instead of target customers?</li>
<li><strong>Traffic Quality</strong>: Is low-quality audience拖累 performance?</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2>Step 3: Create an Action Plan</h2>
<h3>3.1 Attribution Window Adjustment</h3>
<p>If "impression driver" creatives show poor conversions within a 7-day window, try expanding to 28 days (for high-ticket items). Modify attribution settings in Campaign Settings:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Click attribution window: 7 days → 14 days<br />
View attribution window: 1 day → 7 days</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>3.2 Creative Optimization Tactics</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Issue</th>
<th>Action</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Unclear CTA</td>
<td>Use more direct action language</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Slow landing page</td>
<td>Optimize page or use Instant Experience</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Audience mismatch</td>
<td>Create new audience package for this creative</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Creative fatigue</td>
<td>Change thumbnail or first 3 seconds</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>3.3 Documentation Template</h3>
<p>Complete after each review:</p>
<pre><code>Creative ID: [    ]
Account: [    ]
Impression Driver Metrics: [CTR / CPM / Completion Rate]
Revenue Metrics: [ROAS / CPA / Conversion Count]
Quadrant: [A / B / C / D]
Diagnosis: [Specific cause]
Decision: [Pause / Continue testing / Replicate at scale]
Owner: [    ] Date: [    ]
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Q: How to evaluate one creative running across multiple ad sets?</strong></p>
<p>Tag creatives by number in ad set naming. Aggregate data by creative dimension during reviews.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What if my small-budget account lacks data?</strong></p>
<p>Extend review periods to 14 days and lower the "revenue generator" threshold to 5 conversions.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Is high CTR good for conversion-optimized campaigns?</strong></p>
<p>Not necessarily. High CTR with low conversions triggers Meta's algorithm to reduce impressions—this is exactly the danger of Quadrant D creatives. Review and replace promptly.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Quick Checklist</h2>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Export Top 20 creative data</li>
<li>[ ] Calculate CTR / CPM / ROAS ratios</li>
<li>[ ] Complete four-quadrant classification</li>
<li>[ ] Audit landing pages for Quadrant D creatives</li>
<li>[ ] Test attribution window adjustments</li>
<li>[ ] Complete documentation and follow up</li>
</ul>
